    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can transferred employees be furloughed by a new employer? </th>
        <th>If the employee is employed by one employer on 19 March but is transferred to another employer under the TUPE scheme later, they can be furloughed by the new employer.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I prepare for any future lockdown? </th>
        <th>It is advisable to anticipate potential lockdown periods in the future by implementing a lay-off (short-time working) clause into the employment contracts.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can public sector employees be furloughed? </th>
        <th>Public sector employees are not expected to be furloughed. This is because they are usually required to provide essential services. However, this is not a hard rule and if they are not providing essential services they can be furloughed.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How much can I claim under the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme? </th>
        <th>Employers can claim 80% of an employee's salary up to �2,500 per month. In addition, you can claim Employer National Insurance contributions and auto-enrolment pension contributions that are payable at a reduced rate.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>To be eligible for the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme, do I need to prove that I cannot otherwise pay employees ? </th>
        <th>It is not a requirement that the employer cannot otherwise pay its employees or that they need to make employees redundant. An employer can furlough workers if the instruction is given by reason of circumstances arising as a result of coronavirus or coronavirus disease.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What information do I need to submit to apply to the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme? </th>
        <th>The Government has published a step-by-step guide. https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/884664/Coronavirus_Job_Retention_Scheme_step_by_step_guide_for_employers.pdf. The information required is: 1. The number of employees to be furloughed; 2. The dates from and to which employees have been furloughed; 3. Details of employees - the name and National Insurance Number of each furloughed employee; 4. Your employer PAYE scheme reference number; 5. Your Corporation Tax Unique Taxpayer Reference, Self-Assessment Unique Taxpayer Reference or Company Registration Number as appropriate for your entity; 6. Your UK bank account details; 7. Your organisation's registered name; 8. Your organisation's address</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th> </th>
        <th> </th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>To apply to the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme, what steps will I need to take? </th>
        <th>To use the scheme, you need to take 5 steps.:1. check if you can claim.2. check which employees you can put on furlough.3. calculate 80% of your employees� wages.4. claim for your employees� wages.5. report a payment in PAYE Real Time Information.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Do employers need a written agrement with their employees to be eligible for furlough pay? </th>
        <th>Initially, to be eligible for making an application under the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme, the original Direction stated that employers must have obtained the agreement of their employees in writing (in electronic format: email, for instance) that they will cease all work in relation to their employment, and must have kept this on record. The Treasury Direction has removed this requirement for agreement in writing, instead stating the agreement between employer and employee must specify the main terms and conditions upon which the employee will cease all work in relation to their employment. Besides, this agreement must be incorporated into the employee's contract, be made or confirmed in writing by the employer and a record of it has to be kept until 30 June 2025.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Is the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme a public fund for immigration purposes? </th>
        <th>Payments under the Scheme are not public funds and claims can be made for employees on all categories of visas.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What do I need to do to apply to the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme? </th>
        <th>To make a claim under the scheme, you need: a) to be registered for PAYE online; b) your UK bank account number and sort code (only provide bank account details where a BACS payment can be accepted); c) the billing address on your bank account (this is the address on your bank statements); d) your employer PAYE scheme reference number; e) the number of employees being furloughed and each employee�s National Insurance number (you will need to search for their number if you do not have it or contact HMRC if your employee does not have a number); f) each employee�s payroll or employee number (optional); g) the start date and end date of the claim; h) the full amounts that you�re claiming for including: employee wages; employer National Insurance contributions; employer minimum pension contributions; i) your phone number; j) contact nameYou also need to provide either:- your name (or the employer�s name if you�re an agent) or- your Corporation Tax unique taxpayer reference or- your Self Assessment unique taxpayer reference or- your company registration number</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Is a written agreement required to furlough employees? </th>
        <th>An employee's written agreement is no longer required for furloughed employees. However, an agreement must still be reached and it must be confirmed in writing by the employer alone. Evidence of the agreement must be kept until at least 30 June 2025.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can the agreement to furlough be collective? </th>
        <th>The agreement to furlough can be reached via collective agreement between employer and trade union. However, please note that the evidence must be kept in writing until at least 30 June 2025.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>In what circumstances can my employees claim non-discretionary variable payments? </th>
        <th>Non-discretionary variable payments such as fees, commission and overtime can be claimed only if they arise from a legally enforceable agreement.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can my employee claim commission or overtime when furloughed? </th>
        <th>An employee cannot be on unpaid leave and furloughed at the same time. If an employee went on unpaid leave before 1 March 2020, they cannot be furloughed until the agreed period of unpaid leave expires. This is unless an agreement was reached to vary the end date of the unpaid leave after the leave began, and before 20 March 2020.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What are my duties as the company director during the time of being furloughed? </th>
        <th>More detail is provided on the duties that company directors can perform whilst furloughed. Permitted duties include fulfilling statutory duties such as filing accounts, making claims under the Scheme and paying staff salary/wages.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can a furlough agreement be reached? </th>
        <th>Pension scheme trustees can fulfil their duties whilst furloughed, without this counting as work.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Does the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme cover employees who stopped working? </th>
        <th>An employee who was on an employer's payroll on or before 19 March can be re-employed and placed on the furlough scheme even if they stopped working.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Do I have to re-employ workers who stopped working before Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme came into force? </th>
        <th>The employer is not obliged to re-employ employees in order to place them under the furlough scheme.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What is a flexible furlough? </th>
        <th>As of 1 July 2020,flexible furlough will enable employers to return their employees to work part-time whilst remaining on furlough scheme. Employers can decide on shift patterns. However, they will be responsible for paying wages for the work done.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How will the available furlough grant change in the nearest future? </th>
        <th>In June and July 2020, the furlough grant will include coverage of 80% of wages up to a �2,500 cap, but employers will pay for any hours of work. In August 2020, the furlough grant will remain an 80% coverage up to a �2,500 cap, but employers will pay pension contributions, ER and NICs. In September 2020, the furlough grant will include a 70% coverage with a �2,187 cap and the employer will pay ER, NICs, pension and 10% towards 80% of the wages with a cap of �2,500. In October 2020, the grant will cover 60% of wages capped at �1,875, and the employer will pay pension contributions, ER and NICs and 20% towards 80% of the wages with a cap of �2,500.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Does the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme cover new employees? </th>
        <th>The Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme only covers employees who were on a PAYE payroll on or before 19 March 2020.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What is a 'furloughed employee'? </th>
        <th>An employee is furloughed if the employer has instructed them to stop working, or they stopped working for 3 weeks because of circumstances arising as a result of coronavirus.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can furloughed employees undertake training? </th>
        <th>Employees placed on the furlough leave under the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme can undertake training or courses that are 'directly relevant' to their job.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can furloughed employees take courses? </th>
        <th>Furloughed employees cannot provide any services, undertake any work activities, or generate any revenue in relation to the employment from which they have been furloughed (or in regard to any organisation linked to the employer). Should the course in question not fall under any of the above categories, it is compliant with the guidance.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Does the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme cover pension scheme trustees? </th>
        <th>Yes, it does. As long as the pension scheme trustees fulfill their duties, their actions do not count towards work for the purposes of the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I place someone on part-time under the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme? </th>
        <th>If an employee is working on reduced hours or for reduced pay, they are not eligible for this scheme.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can employees on family-related leave be furloughed? </th>
        <th>Statutory payment for family related leave cannot be claimed under the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme because they can already be reclaimed from the Government. Employers can reclaim enhanced contractual pay, such as enhanced maternity pay.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can foreign nationals be furloughed? </th>
        <th>Yes, foreign nationals on all types of visa allowing a right to work can be furloughed, provided that they satisfy the necessary requirements.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can an employee be furloughed by multiple employers? </th>
        <th>Yes, every employer can furlough their employees.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can an employee be furloughed by one employer and still work for another? </th>
        <th>Yes, every employer should be treated separately. An employee can be furloughed by one employer but still work for another one.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can employees come on and off furlough? </th>
        <th>Employees can be furloughed multiple times provided that each period lasts for at least 3 weeks.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can employees be furloughed from various jobs? </th>
        <th>Yes, employees with more than one employment can be furloughed by each of the employers. Note that the cap of the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme applies separately to each job.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I place apprentices on furlough? </th>
        <th>Yes, you can place apprentices on furlough. Note, however, that if their training continues, they have to be paid the apprenticeship national minimum wage (at least) for that time.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can an employee demand to be placed under the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme? </th>
        <th>The employee cannot demand to be furloughed. It is for employers to instruct employees to stop working.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th> </th>
        <th> </th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can zero-hours workers be furloughed? </th>
        <th>Zero-hours workers can be furloughed if they are on PAYE. The median income will have to be calculated.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What happens if the employee refuses to be placed on the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme? </th>
        <th>If the employee refuses to be furloughed and you still decide to do it, you might face an unfair dismissal claim.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Are there any requirements on how to make a selection of the employees to be furloughed? </th>
        <th>There is no general criterion for selection of employees to be furloughed. When deciding on the individuals to be furloughed the employer needs to ensure they do not discriminate on the basis of protected characteristics.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Do I have to consult employees when placing them on furlough? </th>
        <th>In order to place an employee under the Job Retention Scheme, the employer has to consult them and receive an agreement.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Does the employer have to top up the wages of furloughed employees? </th>
        <th>The guidance states that it is for the employers to decide whether to top-up the wages (extra 20% or anything bringing the wages above �2,500). However, under their contract employees are usually entitiled to their full wages. It is advised to discuss the situation with employees.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Does being furloughed affect continuity of employment? </th>
        <th>As the employment contract continues to apply during furlough leave, it should not affect continuity of employment.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I continue to furlough some employees if my business reopens? </th>
        <th>Yes, as long as the employees are eligible under the sceme.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can employers keep employees on furlough when the government scheme ends? </th>
        <th>Yes, if the employees continue to agree to being furloughed, it will be possible to extend this period. However, you will no longer be able to reclaim salary or other wage costs from the scheme after it ends.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can employers keep employees on furlough with reduced terms when the government scheme ends? </th>
        <th>Yes, with employees' agreement. You will need a new furlough agreement depending on new terms. </th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I lay off my employee if there is an existing contractual right to do so? </th>
        <th>You may rely on the contractual right. However, such provision is an implied term of trust and confidence, meaning that you should consult with your employee and give reasonable notice to avoid any breach of contract.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can my employees who have been laid off claim any statutory payments? </th>
        <th>Yes, there are specific statutory provisions for those who have been laid off for 4 or more consecutive weeks in any 13-week period, to claim a statutory redundancy payment. However, this is only if they resign first.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What if my employees do not agree to an extended furlough period? </th>
        <th>You will need to look at other options depending on your workforce requirements.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can my employees withdraw consent to being furloughed? </th>
        <th>No, not if they have agreed in writing to a specific period of furlough.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can my employees refuse extension of a furlough period? </th>
        <th>Yes, they can refuse to agree for furlough period to be extended after the initial agreed period had expired.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I reduce hours and pay for my employees? </th>
        <th>Yes, but only with the employees' agreement. Alternatively, if there is a contractual right to impose short-working, it may be used instead.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I reduce pay and request my employees to work the same hours? </th>
        <th>Yes, with employees' agreement. However, it may be difficult to persuade the employee. You must ensure that you explain the rationale, reasons and business cost in detail.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What if an employee refuses to proposed changes to pay or working hours? </th>
        <th>If an employee refuses after additional time and discussion, you must decide whether to impose change by dismissal and re-engagement on the new terms or adopt different measures.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I dismiss my employee if they refuse to proposed changes? </th>
        <th>Dismissals in such circumstances may be considered as fair, so long as there is a clear business necessity for the change and to follow a fair process. </th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Are there any alternative options to redundancy while on furlough? </th>
        <th>Yes, you may wish to discuss options such as unpaid statutory parental leave or granting unpaid sabbaticals which will enable employees to remain employed without pay until the situation improves.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I make my employees that are on furlough redundant? </th>
        <th>Yes, the employees' redundancy rights continue to apply while on furlough. However, there is a risk of HMRC questioning the rapid redundancies especially when the furlough schemes are available to maintain workforce.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What notice pay is an employee entiteld to on furlough? </th>
        <th>Employees can be either given notice or they can be paid in lieu.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What is the statutory pay notice period for employee on furlough? </th>
        <th>It is one week per year of service and can be up to 12 weeks.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What is the statutory pay notice period for employees who are on furlough due to sickness and with notice less than required under statutory period? </th>
        <th>Notice will be paid based on their pre-furlough pay. They will be entitled to one statutory week pay during their notice period. If employee had various shift patterns, it will be based on their average week pay in the past 12 weeks.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Should I make a payment in lieu of notice if contractual clause exists? </th>
        <th>If you decide to do so, you should firstly check the contract for the advised amount. If it is suggested to be calculated based on basic pay, this would mean normal pay under furlough circumstances.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can employers reclaim notice pay under the government scheme? </th>
        <th>It seems that you should be able to reclaim notice pay if an employee is given notice during furlough for the weeks of notive which fall within the furlough period. Although you cannot reclaim any top-up to usual pay.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can employers calculate statutory redundancy payment for employees on furlough? </th>
        <th>The statutory redundancy payment is calculated based on the years of service, age and one week's pay (which is capped at �538). </th>
    </tr>
