    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can the HMRC impose penalties on businesses making claims under the Scheme? </th>
        <th>Yes. According to the upcoming Finance Bill 2020, the taxman would be able to penalise those businesses that deliberately claim for employees they haven't furloughed or for money they aren't entitled to receive. Directors should expect being liable for tax charges if they have deliberately flouted the rules.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Will be HMRC given the power to recover payments? </th>
        <th>The government started a short consultation on enforcement measures and is states that HMRC be given powers to recover payments where a Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme payment has not been used to pay employees, make pensions contributions, pay PAYE or National Insurance contributions. HMRC could also take criminal action in cases of fraud.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How long organisations must retain their records? </th>
        <th>The following records must be retained by organisations for six years: the amount claimed and claim period for each employee; the claim reference number; their calculations.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I compel my employee to take annual leave during furlough? </th>
        <th>If your employees will not take holiday during furlough, they may be due up to eight months's worth of holiday pay upon their return to work or when their employment ends.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Why should I encourage my employees to take annual leave during furlough? </th>
        <th>For a number of reasons such as (1) to encourage employees to look out for their own wellbeing and health, (2) to reduce the amount of leave to be taken once work resumes and (3) to take advantage of the financial assistance via the CJRS in funding annual leave payments.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What is the notice period for annual leave during furlough? </th>
        <th>The notice periods remain the same with employers being required to give double the length of the holiday that the employer wishes the employee to take.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Should I encourage to take annual leave to my staff that is not furloughed? </th>
        <th>Yes, you should still encourage staff to use their holidays to avoid having a large number of requests towards the end of the year.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Are employers obliged to equip their employees working from home? </th>
        <th>Yes, they are. Employers should take every possible step to facilitate employees working from home, including the supply of suitable IT and equipment to enable remote working.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can my employee request to work from home? </th>
        <th>Employees will have a statutory right to request to work from home if they have at least 6 months of service. You will have to deal with such requests in a reasonable manner by assessing advantages and disadvantages, holding a meeting to discuss the request and offering an appeal right if the request is refused.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>When can a requst to work from home be made? </th>
        <th>A statutory request can only be made once in any 12-month period and so employees should consider the proposed change(s) they are seeking carefully before submitting the request.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Is it a requirement for the request to work from home to be in writing? </th>
        <th>Yes, it must be in writing and must include (1) application date, (2) details of change, (3) preferred enforcement date, (4) impact on employer and (5) statement confirming statutory request and any dates of previous requests made.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I deny a request to work from home? </th>
        <th>You will need to discuss the application with the employee before considering not granting the request. You must hold a meeting with the employee to discuss the application and allow the employee to be accompanied by a work colleague at that meeting.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>In what circumstances can I reject a request to work from home? </th>
        <th>Possible reasons may include burden of additional costs, inability to recognise work,inability to recruit extra staff, detrimental impact on quality and performance or meeting customer needs. Other reasons may include insufficient work or planned structural change to your business.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>When should I respond to a request to work from home? </th>
        <th>Statutory requests must be dealt within three months from the date of receipt, unless the employee agrees to a longer period for the request to be dealt with.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>My employee has worked less than 6 months. Can they request to work from home? </th>
        <th>If they have not worked long enough to make a statutory request, they can still make a non-statutory request for a flexible working arrangement, although the process will not be the same in considering the application.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I refuse a request to work from home if my employee has recently returned from maternity or parental leave? </th>
        <th>You must not discriminate unlawfully when determining any flexible working requests. It will be unlawful discrimination if you refuse a flexible working arrangement because the employee making the request has recently returned from maternity leave or other parental leave.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What impact will Covid-19 have on flexible working practices in the future? </th>
        <th>It is too early to tell what impact COVID-19 will have on flexible working practices in the UK. However, many employees will wish to spend more of their time working from home in the future. Employers will have found during the lockdown period that home working can work well and does not necessarily conflict with the needs of the business.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can employers ensure the high data security while employees are working from home? </th>
        <th>The employers can adapt to the new ways of working and minimise risks of data breaches by taking the following steps: 1). Ask employees to use a separate work space for sensitive calls; 2). Use privacy screens; 3). Do not share technology computers with others; 4). Shred confidential information; 5). Provide security trainings for employees.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What are the ways of monitoring the employees activities  while they are working from home? </th>
        <th>The traditional way of monitoring employees includes internet use and email content, regular calls and traffic. However, with the recent rapid development of flexi working, many employers introduce extreme methods of surveillance, which include capturing keystrokes, taking screenshots every ten minutes and logging websites.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Which legislation governs the monitoring of employees? </th>
        <th>There is a variety of legislation governing the monitoring of employees. The relevant regulation or Act will depend on what you are monitoring and why. The legislation can include the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000, the Investigatory Powers Act 2016, the Investigatory Powers Regulations 2018, as well as the General Data Protection Regulation applicable EU-wide.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Are an employer�s policies and its monitoring of its employees legal? </th>
        <th>The following should be considered in determining the legality of monitoring: 1) Inform employees of the intention to monitor2) Be mindful of the risks around discrimination3) Ensure sufficient safeguards are put in place to prevent abuse4) Act in a proportionate and justified manner e.g. in respect of the method used </th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What are my duties as an employer at the workplace? </th>
        <th>There is a statutory duty to ensure health, safety and welfare of every employee and members of the public 'so far as is reasonably practical'. The employer has to assess risks, and set up and implement a safe system of work.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What are my duties towards contractors at the workplace? </th>
        <th>There is a duty to ensure safety of visitors and contractors 'so far as is reasonably practical'. The employer has to assess risks, and set up and implement a safe system of work.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What are the rules on having visitors at the workplace? </th>
        <th>Government guidelines suggest minimising the number of unnecessary visits. When visits/contacts are necessary and cannot be undertaken by remote connection, guidance on social distancing and hygiene should be explained prior to arrival and on arrival (for example, by signage). The number of visitors must be limited and a visiting record must be kept. Contact with visitors must be minimal. People acting as hosts must receive the necessary COVID-19 training.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I ask my employees to travel to work? </th>
        <th>You should encourage your employees to travel to work by walking, cycling or driving rather than using public transport. However, this is not a clear and strict duty and when absolutely necessary employees can travel by public transport.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can my employees travel for work-related reasons? </th>
        <th>It is best to avoid unnecessary work travel. When it is unavoidable, minimise the number of people travelling by one vehicle, ensure that the vehicle has good ventilation, and that the employees do not sit face-to-face. Should employees need to stay away from their home (for work reasons), ensure that any overnight accommodation meets social distancing guidelines. Employees delivering the goods should adhere to the hygiene and distancing guidelines.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Do social distancing rules apply when handling accidents and emergencies? </th>
        <th>The priority in an accident remains safety. In an emergency situation (e.g. an accident, chemical spill, fire, break-in), employees do NOT have to stay two metres apart.People assisting others should pay attention to sanitation immediately after handling the accident, emergency (i.e. by washing hands).</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What cleaning facilities should I provide at the workplace? </th>
        <th>When employees return to work you need to increase frequency of handwashing and surface cleaning by providing hand sanitisers around the workplace, cleaning and disinfecting objects and surfaces that are regularly touched, setting cleaning guidelines for toilets and providing hand drying facilities.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th> </th>
        <th> </th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I ensure social distancing at the workplace? </th>
        <th>When employees return to work, where possible, you need to maintain 2m distance between your employees by placing signs around the space with reminders about social distancing rules, avoiding sharing workstations, using floor tape for marking 2m distance, arranging one-way traffic and inviting visitors only by appointment if possible</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I ensure the safety of the employees working in other people's homes? </th>
        <th>Where possible, the employees should avoid travelling to sites by public transport.Where employees have no option but to travel together, for example in delivery teams, the following should be encouraged:- journeys should be with the same individuals and a limit should be set to the number of people travelling per vehicle.- maintaining good ventilation, for example keeping windows open and passengers facing away from one another.- vehicles should be regularly cleaned with emphasis on handles and other areas where passengers may touch surfaces.- where possible, employers or agencies should match workers to households local to them to minimise transportation.- employees must also wash hands on arrival and maintain social distancing when entering the home.With respect to appointments in other people's homes:- Remote working tools should be used to avoid in-person appointments.- Only those participants who are absolutely necessary should attend appointments and should maintain two-metre separation where possible.- Meetings should be held outdoors or in well-ventilated rooms whenever possible.- Pens and other objects should NOT be shared during appointments.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I ensure the safety of employees working in and from vehicles? </th>
        <th>It is advised to maintain social distancing even when inside the vehicles by a) avoiding multiple occupancy vehicles if possible; b) when vehicles have to be shared by the employees, to minimise the risk of spreading the virus by having a single person (or contactless) refuelling if possible and/or use physical screening, provided this does not compromise safety, for example, through reducing visibility. Employees should be sitting side-by-side, instead of face-to-face. In addition, vehicles should be cleaned frequently and have sufficient ventilation and/or open windows.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I ensure safe movement around buildings and worksites? </th>
        <th>Employers would usually need to comply with the following steps. a) discourage unnecessary trips around and within the buildings and sites - for instance, access to certain areas could be restricted. b) adoption of a one-way only flow via the buildings/sites. c) reduce maximum occupancy for elevators. d) regulate movements and use of busy areas, such as corridors and walkways. e) reduce equipment rotation.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What should I do if it is impossible to keep 2m distance at the workplace? </th>
        <th>If you cannot ensure that people are kept 2m away from each other, you should do everything possible to manage risk of transmission by considering whether it is necessary to proceed with the activity in order for the business to operate, keeping that activity as short as possible, using barriers between people, staggering arrival and departure.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Is it safe for my employees to return to work? </th>
        <th>As of 18 May 2020, employees should be actively encouraged to return to work if they cannot work from home. However, they should avoid using public transport if possible.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>As an employer, do I have a duty to inform my employees about the latest health and safety policies? </th>
        <th>If you (viz. employer) employ five or more employees, then you must have a written statement setting out the general health and safety policy with respect to the employees and the organisation (a health and safety policy), and the arrangements for carrying out the policy.The company's health and safety policy, and any revision of it, must be brought to the attention of all employees.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I re-open my business? </th>
        <th>There has been no change in the types of businesses that should remain closed to the public (e.g. pubs, gyms, restaurants and cinemas) but businesses that have been permitted to remain open and whose employees are unable to work from home will be able to have their staff return to work.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I determine whether my business is safe to re-open? </th>
        <th>You will remain bound by health and safety obligations to ensure a safe place of work. You should regularly carry out risk assessments within your business to identify the extent to of exposure to contracting and/or spreading COVID-19. You should also consult employees on steps taken  towards risk management and update employee emergency contact details.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Am I required to I test my employees for Covid-19? </th>
        <th>Currently, there is no requirement to carry out tests on employees.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I consult my employees before actively encouraging them to return to work? </th>
        <th>You may circulate surveys amongst the workforce in advance or encourage virtual meetings to discuss all aspects of the return to work. In the survey you may wish to include questions relating to comfort of return, any concerns or opinion on new policies imposed.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Do employees have any health and safety responsibilities? </th>
        <th>Yes, employees have health and safety responsibilities at work. These include taking reasonable care for their health and safety and that of anyone who may be affected by their acts or omissions at work; and to co-operate with their employer so far as is necessary to enable compliance with any statutory duty or requirement relating to health and safety.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Are there any practical steps I can take to ensure that my employees remain safe whilst at work? </th>
        <th>You may  (1) impose social distancing including keeping 2m apart, avoiding lifts if possible, prohibiting large group meetings, (2) manage transmission risk by introducing shift pattern and (3) encourage hygiene by offering sanitizers and placing signs or posters.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What can I do to protect my employees continuing to travel to the workplace? </th>
        <th>As an employer, you should ensure the safety of your employees by a) digitalising the transfer of any materials; b) avoiding face-to-face interactions, unless it is essential, in which case time-limiting these interactions to 15 minutes; c) transforming staff canteens into takeaway points and urging the employees to bring homemade food; d) updating the employees regularly on the latest safety guidance by making announcements.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What can I do to safeguard the mental health of my employees? </th>
        <th>You should review the support that you are able to provide, preferably well in advance of any planned return to work.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Is it mandatory for the employees to use PPE (Personal Protective Equipment) at the workplace? </th>
        <th>While the UK Government's Guidelines advise that employers already utilising PPE at their workplace should continue doing so, it is also suggested that additional PPE (beyond that already employed) is not beneficial. This is because the virus-related risks are to be managed via social distancing and hygiene, not PPE. The guidelines clearly stipulate that a) workplaces should not encourage the precautionary use of extra PPE to protect against COVID-19 outside clinical settings or when responding to a suspected or confirmed case of COVID-19;b) unless a workplace is in a situation where the risk of COVID-19 transmission is very high, a risk assessment should reflect the fact that the role of PPE in providing additional protection is extremely limited;c) if a risk assessment shows that PPE is required it must be provided free of charge to workers who need it. Any PPE provided must fit properly.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Do employees need to wear face masks at work? </th>
        <th>Wearing a face mask in the workplace is optional and is not required by law, as of 06.06.2020. Having said that, should employees decide to wear face coverings, employers must ensure they do so safely. Employers should tell their employees the following. 1) wash hands thoroughly with the use of soap and water for 20 seconds (and above) or, alternatively, use hand sanitiser before putting a face covering on and taking it off.2) avoid touching the face or face mask while it is on.3) change the face covering if it becomes damp or after touching it.4) continue washing hands on a regular basis.5) change and wash a face covering on a daily basis or dispose of it should it not be washable.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What should I do if I cannot accommodate employees who are in the high risk category? </th>
        <th>If it is not possible to accommodate remote working for such employees, you should ask them to offer to work only if you are able to provide a safe option for them to do so. If it is not possible to make alternative arrangements for these individuals, you could consider furloughing these employees.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Are there any categories of employees which I should give special consideration to? </th>
        <th>Yes. You should give special consideration to those falling into the extremely vulnerable and high-risk categories such as pregnant employees, employees over 70, employees with childcare responsibilities and those with underlying health conditions or to anyone who is living with an individual in the extremely vulnerable category.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What should I do if my employee refuses to return to work? </th>
        <th>If all reasonable steps have been taken in respect of health and safety but an employee refuses to return to work, there are other options which you could consider such as encouraging taking holiday entitlement or unpaid leave.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I insist that employees come into work? </th>
        <th>You should avoid threatening employees with disciplinary measures or dismissal if they are unwilling to return to work due to a risk of contracting COVID-19, as this could give rise to a claim. All employees have the right not to be subjected to any detriment on the grounds that they refuse to return to work in circumstances �where they reasonably believe there to be serious and imminent danger�.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>In what circumstances should I urge my employees not to come to work? </th>
        <th>Whenever an employee is experiencing symptoms of COVID-19 or has been recommended to self-isolate in line with the UK Government's 'Test and Trace' strategy, or is sharing a household with a person who has symptoms, they must not come to work.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What are the guidelines regarding arriving at and leaving work? </th>
        <th>The objective set out in the UK Government's guidelines is to ensure social distancing on arrival and departure and handwashing upon arrival. Recommended steps are as follows. a) staggering arrival and departure times to reduce crowding into and out of the workplace (it should take account of the impact on those with protected/special characteristics).b) provision of additional parking or facilities such as bike racks.c) limiting passengers in corporate vehicles, for example, work minibuses (this could include leaving seats empty).d) reducing congestion, for example, by having more entry points to the workplace.e) providing more storage for workers for clothes and bags. Where people are working in a restaurant it is suggested that uniforms should be washed on site rather than by individual staff members at home.f) sign markings and introducing one-way flow at entry and exit points.g) providing handwashing facilities, or hand sanitiser where not possible, at entry and exit points and providing alternatives to touch-based security devices such as keypads.h) adjusting procedures at entry or exit points where appropriate; for example, by deactivating turnstiles requiring pass checks and having passes checked by security personnel at a distance.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What is the guidance on workplaces/workstations? </th>
        <th>The steps that an employer would usually have to take to ensure the safety of their employees. 1) If sharing workstations is unavoidable they should be shared by the smallest possible number of people. 2) Workstations must be kept two metres away from one another. If that is not possible the business should consider whether the activity in question needs to continue for the business to operate and, if so, take all mitigating actions possible to reduce the risk of transmission: people should work side-by-side or facing away from each other rather than face-to-face and screens should be used to separate people. 3) Where using hot desks and spaces cannot be avoided, cleaning workstations and shared equipment between occupants are the steps to be taken. 4) put floor tape or paint to mark areas, helping workers keep to a two-metre distance. In addition, the guidelines for restaurants also make specific suggestions for food preparation areas. The guidelines suggest limiting access to kitchens to as few people as possible and minimising interaction between kitchen staff and other workers, including when on breaks. Using one way traffic flows is suggested together with floor markings and keeping workstations two metres apart. Restaurants should limit access to walk-in pantries, fridges and freezers, for example, with only one person being able to access these areas at one point in time and should minimise contact at handover points with other staff, such as when presenting food to serving staff and delivery drivers.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Do social distancing rules apply to common areas, such as receptions? </th>
        <th>The Government has provided a particular set of steps to ensure safety in communal areas. a) In multi-tenant sites or buildings, businesses will need to work collaboratively with landlords and other tenants to ensure consistency across common areas, for example, receptions and staircases.b) In receptions and similar areas, install screens to protect staff.c) Regulate use of locker rooms, changing areas and other facility areas to reduce concurrent usage. Encourage storage of personal items and clothing in lockers or other personal storage spaces.d) Stagger break times to reduce pressure on break rooms or canteens. Use safe outside areas for breaks or create space by using other parts of the workplace that have been freed up by remote working.e) Avoid fully opening staff canteens by providing packaged meals and encouraging staff to bring their own food. Arrange seating and tables to maintain spacing and reduce face-to-face interactions.f) Encouraging staff to remain on-site and, when not possible, maintaining social distancing while off-site.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can in-person meetings still take place? </th>
        <th>To reduce transmission of COVID-19, in-person meetings should be avoided by using remote working tools. Having said that, in-person meetings can take place when no alternative solution can be found. In such circumstances, only those absolutely necessary should attend the in-person meeting, maintaining two-metre separation throughout. Hand sanitiser should be provided in meeting rooms and pens and other objects should not be shared. Meeting rooms should be well-ventilated, and thought should be given to holding meetings outdoors. In addition, for areas where regular meetings take place, floor signage must be used to help people maintain social distancing.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>When should I review existing risk assessment? </th>
        <th>Any risk assessment should be reviewed if there is a reason to suspect that it is no longer valid or if there is a significant change in the matter to which it relates. An open and focussed revision of previous working patterns, shifts and the overall approach to each key area of the work in question may well be required.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What matters do I need to consider in a risk assessment? </th>
        <th>Each employer has to consider a specific size as well as nature of their business, the way it is organised, operated, managed, and regulated. Besides, employees, contractors, agency workers, and other categories of people should be accounted for when conducting their assessment.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Do employers need to share information about the risk assessment with their employees? </th>
        <th>Employers must provide their employees with the following information. 1) The risks to the employee's health and safety identified as a result of the assessment. 2) Procedures to follow in case of a serious and imminent danger to the staff. 3) Identify the persons responsible for evacuation of the workplace. 4) The preventive and protective measures that the risk assessment has shown the employer it needs to take to comply with its legal obligations.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What approach should I take when conducting risk re-assessment? </th>
        <th>Ensure health and safety of employees so far as is reasonably practicable by taking a focused approach to re-assessing the altered risk profile. Where the standard social distancing advice is impossible, the setting of suitable and sufficient risk assessment and coordinating the system of work will help to prove that, far from any alleged recklessness, you are acting appropriately and provably in line with advice from the government, experts and industry bodies.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What measures should I take upon return to work? </th>
        <th>Depending on your organisation, you should evaluate and decide on what activities may be continued and/or adapted, depending on specificity and available resources, and implement necessary measures for resuming and/or maintaining the activity, with the observance of relevant prevention measures, including work from home or telework.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What do I need to do to start running my business after lockdown? </th>
        <th>The UK Government has suggested 5 key steps to be taken by emploters when emerging from lockdown and returning to work. 1) COVID-19 risk assessment must be carried out. 2) Sufficient cleaning, washing, and hygiene procedures must be put in place. 3) Employers must also provide reasonable help to people to work from home. 4) Maintenance of 2 metre social distancing (if possible). 5) Where social distancing rules cannot be complied with, transmission risk has to be managed (ie reducing the number of employees, using barriers and other measures).</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Do employers need to communicate with employees before their return to work? </th>
        <th>Yes, employers have to communicate witht heir workforce prior to (and after) the emplyees' return to the workplace. This should be done to enable and support their return to work (including mental health support) and inform of the steps the employees would be required to take on the return to work as well as of COVID-19-related safety procedures.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What exactly do I need to tell my employees when returning to work? </th>
        <th>You should tell your employees when exactly you are planning to return to work and update them on health and safety measures that you are implementing. You should also conduct a consultation about different adjustments to work, for example new shift patterns.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Shall I continue employing homeworking policy after lockdown? </th>
        <th>The UK Government has provided a cogent message for the employers to continue emplying homeworking (if possible). Note, however, the employers would have to check whether their existing homeworking policy meets the new circumstances and amend it in accordance with the UK Government's guidance.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What workforce problems can I, an employer, face after the lockdown? </th>
        <th>The key issues that have to be dealth with include potential sickness absence (ie need to self-isolate), vulnerable employees (ie clinically vulnerable), mental health issues experienced by the employees, employees' fitness for work (ie COVID-19 symptoms), commuting and attendance at the workplace.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What can I do to limit the risk for my employees of becoming in close contact? </th>
        <th>You may implement phased-out working schedules for employees (especially for vulnerable groups) in order to limit direct contact between employees, but without affecting the length of the regular working hours.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What should I do if I have a large number of employees? </th>
        <th>If you are hiring more than 50 employees, you have an obligation to establish phased-out work schedules, without the need to obtain employee consent. The start time and end time take place in intervals of at least 1 hour, for at least 3 hours, in tranches of at least 20% of the personnel.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I check my employee's temperature upon return to work? </th>
        <th>You must conduct epidemiologic triage through temperature screening and symptoms observation, for both employees and visitors. You may want to assign a person responsible with the epidemiologic triage.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What steps can I take to ensure that my employees are keeping up with their hygiene upon return to work? </th>
        <th>You should inform your employees on maintaining rigorous hygiene by using soap and water for at least 20 seconds, avoiding touching of the face with unsensitised hands, sneezing in the elbow pad or using a disposable napkin.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What distance should my employees hold upon return to work? </th>
        <th>You should inform employees to limit contact with others to maximum 15 minutes, at a distance of at least 1.5 meters;</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I monitor my employee's heath after return to work? </th>
        <th>You should ensure that constant communication with the doctor/medical service provider responsible for occupational medicine, in order to monitor the employees� health. You may also initiate and conduct consultations with employees� representative(s) holding specific health & safety responsibilities and/or members of the Health & Safety Committee at the company level.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How should I inform my employees on the new health and safety measures? </th>
        <th>You should inform your employees, primarily via electronic means, on the risks of virus contamination, protection measures, social distancing rules applicable at the company level, as well as management of cases involving employees or other persons having access to the workplace who do present CoV-2 symptoms.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What health and safety steps should my employees take upon return to work? </th>
        <th>They should immediately inform you if they manifest Covid-19 symptoms before or upon return to work, wear masks at workplace and submit themselves to temperature screening.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Where should I display manditory conduct rules for employees and employers? </th>
        <th>Mandatory conduct rules for both employees and visitors shall be displayed at the entrance into the workplace and in the most visible places.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What can I do to avoid crowding by my employees? </th>
        <th>You should shall mark and implement specific access paths, as well as movement paths for the employees in order to avoid crowding. In public places, strips marking the recommended distance (1.5 meters) shall be installed.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What can I implement to avoid crowding during lunch breaks? </th>
        <th>You should ensure phased-out lunch breaks, while observing the minimum distance of 1.5 metre.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What other measures can I take to ensure that the premises are safe for my employees? </th>
        <th>You should also consider air ventilation of the premises to be ensured at least once a day.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What are the consequences of not ensuring safety at the workplace? </th>
        <th>Breach of a duty to ensure safety 'so far as reasonably practical' is a criminal offence. The employer will have to pay a fine if found to breach the duty</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How do I make a risk assessment for covid-19 at the workplace? </th>
        <th>You need to identify who can be harmed and how and what will be the appropriate measures to protect these individuals. </th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What is contact tracing? </th>
        <th>Contact tracing system is triggered when an individual who has been tested positive with Covid-19 or has any symptoms.  Individuals are then contacted and asked about who else they may have been in close contact with.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What does 'close contact' mean? </th>
        <th>Close contact means having face-to-face contact at a distance of less than 1 metre, spending more than 15 minutes within 2 metres of someone, or travelling in a car or close to them on a plane in the two days before and since the individual developed COVID-19 symptoms.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How long should self-isolation last if close contact occured? </th>
        <th>Those identified close contacts will be asked to self-isolate at home for 14 days in line with government guidance.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What should I do if an employee has been asked to self-isolate? </th>
        <th>You will be expected to enable employees to adhere to self-isolation guidelines if they are identified as being in close contact with someone diagnosed with COVID-19.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I test my employees lawfully under data protection rules? </th>
        <th>If you want to test your employees lawfully under data protection rules, the legal basis can be legitimate interest. However, each organisation should make a separate assessment.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I ensure compliance with data protection? </th>
        <th>In order to show that you comply with data protection rules when you test your employees for symptoms of Covid-19, you can conduct a data protection impact assessment. It should set out the activity, data protection risks, necessity and proportionality of the activity, and mitigating actions that can be placed against the risks.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What steps should I take to ensure that I do not collect too much data when testing my employees for symptoms of Covid-19? </th>
        <th>In order to ensure that too much data is not collected when you test your employees for symptoms of Covid-19, you need to ensure that any collection is adequate, relevant and limited to what is necessary. For example, you should only collect the data about tests and not about underlying health conditions.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Am I allowed to keep a list of the employees who have symptoms? </th>
        <th>If you collect data about your employees' symptoms or positive results of Covid-19 tests, you can keep the list of the employees provided that it is secure and duty of confidentiality is observed</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I share with other employees the information that someone has tested positive? </th>
        <th>If one of your employees has tested positive, you should inform the rest of the employees about potential risks. However, it is advised not to name the affected employees.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I install thermal cameras on site for testing of temperature or monitoring? </th>
        <th>If you want to use intrusive technologies in order to make health checks, any monitoring needs to be necessary and proportionate. You should also observe transparency and inform the employees.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can employers be held liable for a data breach by its employee? </th>
        <th>Yes. It depends on the employee�s job and responsibilities undertaken. The employer can be held liable for its employee�s wrongdoing if a breach is closely connected to what an employee is responsible for as part of his/her role within the company.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can employees be personally responsible for a data breach causing loss to the employer? </th>
        <th>Employee might be personally liable for a data breach if s/he had access to a large amount of information as part of the job role and disclosed data with intention to cause damage to the employer.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I reveal the identity of my employee who has been tested positive of Covid-19? </th>
        <th>You may not reveal the identity of the self-isolating employee under the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) as you have a duty to protect the sensitive health information of all employees.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I inform my employees if an employee has been asked to self-isolate? </th>
        <th>You can inform employees who have been in close contact with someone required to self-isolate by the contact tracing service to be more vigilant about monitoring themselves for COVID-19 symptoms (i.e., a high temperature and a new, persistent cough).</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>My employees are unwell with a diagnosed case of Covid-19. Do I have to pay them? </th>
        <th>If your employees are unwell with or have symptoms of Covid-19, they are entitled to receive usual sick leave.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I stop Statutory Sick Pay (SSP) for my employees? </th>
        <th>For Statutory Sick Pay (SSP) purposes, employers and employees can agree to end a period of incapacity for work in order to stop SSP and commence furlough leave instead.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can an employee claim SSP if they have been asked to self-isolate? </th>
        <th>Those employees who meet the earnings criteria will be eligible for Statutory Sick Pay (SSP) of �95.85 (�94.25 before 6 April 2020) from the first day of the period in which they are required to self-isolate.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What if my employee has contractual sick pay benefits? </th>
        <th>Employers that offer more generous contractual sick pay benefits, however, should consider whether they will provide sick pay at the usual contractual rate to those self-isolating.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What is Coronavirus Statutory Sick Pay Rebate Scheme? </th>
        <th>The scheme enables employers that were registered for Pay As You Earn (PAYE) on or before 28 February 2020, and who had fewer than 250 PAYE employees at that date, to reclaim up to two weeks SSP provided to employees.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>When can I re-claim SSP for my employee that is on self-isolation? </th>
        <th>You can claim from the first qualifying day that the employee is off work if the period of sickness has started on or after (1) 13 March 2020 (if has Covid-19,symptoms or self-isolating), (2) 16 April 2020 (if sheilding because of Covid-19) and (3) 28 May 2020 (if identified as close contact).</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What does 'qualifying day' mean for SSP purposes? </th>
        <th>For the purposes of SSP, a quilifying day is the day an employee will usually work on.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Will I need to reclaim SSP from HMRC? </th>
        <th>The Coronavirus Statutory Sick Pay Rebate scheme does require the employer to proactively reclaim this amount from HMRC.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Do I need to keep record of reclaim to SSP? </th>
        <th>You will not be required to keep records of any claims made for three years.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>When will I receive SSP reclaim for my employee on self-isolation? </th>
        <th>HMRC estimates that employers should receive the amounts owed six working days after submission of a claim.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can employees take me to Court if I make them redundant during Covid-19 ourbreak? </th>
        <th>Only employees with two years' continious service are protected from unfair dismissal. A dismissal is unfair unless a) it was for a potentially fair reason listed in the legislation; and b) it was fair in the circumstances. Redundancy is potentially fair reason for dismissal. Redundancy occurs if there is closure of the business, for example. However, it is still unclear whether it will be considered fair when Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme is in place</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What are the consequences of redundancy? </th>
        <th>Redundancies are not a cheap option and, if mistakes are made in the way they are handled, further costs may be incurred on account of tribunal claims. Other drawbacks include the loss of valuable skills and experience and the negative impact on the morale of the staff that are retained.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What are the alternative options to redundancy? </th>
        <th>Changing terms and conditions, changing pension scheme, lay-off and short time working, reducing use of contract workers, discreitonary benefits, re-deployment, secondment, freezing recruitment or flexible working.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I reduce business costs without having to dismiss my employee? </th>
        <th>By changing terms and conditions and adjusting contractual entitlements such as introducing a pay cut or restricting overtime.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What are the consequences of adjusting contractual terms and conditions? </th>
        <th>Changing terms and conditions is fraught with legal dangers and employers should proceed carefully and generally take legal advice before embarking on such a course.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What are the main options for changing terms and conditions? </th>
        <th>Making changes which are allowed under the contract, varation by mutual agreement, unilateral imposition of new terms or terminating employees' contracts and re-engaging them on new terms.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I vary the contractual terms and conditions? </th>
        <th>If the contract includes a 'flexibility clause', this would provide an expressed right to implement any changes. Depending on the clause, it may be a specific clause which covers the proposed change or it may give general power to vary the contract. However, flexibility clause may be restricted due to being ambiguous.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I reduce the hours and pay of my employees? </th>
        <th>Yes, employesr can alter existing terms and conditions of employment. This includes the right to decrease the number of hours (pay cuts) adopted temporarily or on a conditional basis (ie hitting business targets when emerging from the lockdown). Note well, reducing hours can possibly be a permanent change as well.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I change terms and conditions if my organisation is unionised? </th>
        <th>Yes, the changes should be firstly negotiated with the relevant trade union. The changes are likely to be permitted by individual contracts if there is a clause for collectively agreed changes to be automatically incorporated. However, you will need to obtain employees' agreement before accepting proposed changes.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I vary terms and conditions if there are no rights to impose unilateral changes? </th>
        <th>The best route is to obtain employees� consent. Faced with the option of agreeing detrimental changes or potentially being made redundant, many employees are likely to be amenable albeit reluctantly.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I ensure that agreement can be reached with my employees to vary contract? </th>
        <th>Full and effective communication and consultation, so that employees fully understand the business needs behind difficult decisions, is a crucial factor in securing agreement. This can be done via staff briefings and meetings but it is best also to offer individual consultation on a one-to-one basis.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Is it a requirement for the employee agreement to vary contract be written? </th>
        <th>It is essential to obtain employees� individual written agreement to changes, in order to avoid future disputes.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What should I do if my employee refuses to agree to the required change of terms and conditions? </th>
        <th>You may announce that the change will be implemented from a set date. Although this may be a risky strategy as the employees may continue to work but under protest and reserve the right to sue for breach of contract, or resign and claim constructive dismissal.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What would be the best outcome if I simply impose implemented terms from a set date? </th>
        <th>The best outocme would be that the employees acquiesce in the new working arrangements and go along with them. After a period of time, the legal position would be that such employees had impliedly agreed to the variation by their conduct.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What if my employee simply refuses to accept contractual changes? </th>
        <th>Better way to proceed is to terminate their existing employment contracts, giving the required statutory or contractual notice, and offer to re-engage them on new contracts containing the revised terms.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What should I do if my employee claims unfair dismissal? </th>
        <th>Employees with at least two years� service will be entitled to claim unfair dismissal. However, you can defend such claims by showing a �substantial reason� of the pressing business need to introduce the changes. You may also argue that you have adopted a fair procedure by consulting fully over its proposals and acted reasonably in the circumstances.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Is there a legal duty for collective consultation purposes? </th>
        <th>Yes, if 20 or more employees will be dismissed within a 90-day period, you must consult with the recognised trade union if there is one, or elected employee representatives otherwise.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How long shoud consultation period last? </th>
        <th>The consultation period must last at least 60 days to allow consulting with employee representatives.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What is considered as 'lay-off'? </th>
        <th>A lay-off is generally understood to mean an employer providing employees with no work nor pay for a week or more.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>When does short time working occur? </th>
        <th>Short-time working occurs when an employee works only part of a week and receives proportionately reduced pay.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What if I cannot impose lay-off or short-time working for my employee? </th>
        <th>You should consider changing contractual terms and conditions. However, you may potentially face claims for unlawful deduction from wages, breach of contract and constructive dismissal if express and informed consent is obtained from your employee.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Is there any statutory protection of lay-off or short-time working available to my employee? </th>
        <th>Yes, but it is complex and little-used in practice. It provides a right for employees who have been laid off or kept on short time for four or more consecutive weeks or six weeks in any 13-week period to claim a redundancy payment in certain circumstances. The scheme only applies where the contract of employment allows for lay-off/short-time working without pay.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can my employee claim any compensation if they are laid-off without pay? </th>
        <th>There is a statutory wage protection scheme, where the employee can claim guarantee payment for the days which they would normally be required to work. However, there is a cap of �29.00 per day and entitlement is limited only to five days in any three month period.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can I reduce the use of contract workers? </th>
        <th>It may be a relatively low-risk way to reduce employment costs without making �permanent� staff redundant. However, it should be carefully assessed in cases of legally qualifying as �employees� with statutory rights such as statutory redundancy pay and unfair dismissal.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What will happen if I terminate my part-time or fixed-term employee contract? </th>
        <th>You should be careful when terminating part-time or fixed-term staff. They are protected from less favourable treatment in comparison to full-time and permanent colleagues, unless it can be objectively justified by you.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>How can I re-deploy my employees? </th>
        <th>By placing them elsewhere within the organisation wherever possible, or alternatively arrange for them to be seconded to other companies. Please note, this will need to be done with the employee�s consent in the absence of an express right to redeploy or second in the contract of employment.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Should I freeze my recruitment? </th>
        <th>This is an obvious and straightforward way of reducing overheads without fear of legal consequences, especially in cases of high rates of staff turnover.Recruitment deferrals may be another option, although you may need to proceed with caution if they already have committed themselves to a particular start date.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Is it necessary for introduction of flexible working to be made in writing? </th>
        <th>If you plan to introduce flexible working to your employee, you should first seek their consent and then provide details of the new working regime which should be clearly set out in writing.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What should I do if my employee does not consent to flexible working? </th>
        <th>You can seek to rely on any flexibility clauses in the contract or consider terminating and re-engaging on new terms as a final resort.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Are there any practical issues of flexible working? </th>
        <th>You should consider monitoring and recording core hours; access to IT systems and equipment; and health and safety.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>What if my employee holds Tier 2 or Tier 5 Visa? </th>
        <th>Any of the employees who hold a Tier 2 or 5 visa will have reporting requirements that are likely to be triggered in case of redundancy or decising to lay-off, which may then have knock-on implications for whether they can keep their visa or not.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can employers require employees to take or not to take holiday? </th>
        <th>It will depend on whether the holiday is statutory or contractual. Statutory holiday is covered by the Working Time Regulations 1998 and allows the employer to request its employees to take holiday during a specific period as long as employer gives twice as much advance notice as the amount of holiday. Conditions of contractual holiday will depend on the terms of the contract or internal holiday policy.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can employees carry-over their unused leave? </th>
        <th>Yes, the employees are allowed to carry forward the four weeks of leave guaranteed under the European Working Time Directive, where it was not reasonably practicable to take holiday in the current leave year, such as a result of the effect of the coronavirus. The unused leave must be taken within the next two leave years.</th>
    </tr>
    <tr class="cells">
        <th>Can employers reduce employees working hours or ��lay off�� employees for a temporary period without pay? </th>
        <th>It depends on a statutory scheme for reduced working hours and on the employer�s contractual right. In the absence of such a right, employees should consent to the changes to ensure that the new terms will not amount to a breach of contract.</th>
    </tr>
